Overview

We will try out an applied machine learning binary classification demo using the Johns Hopkins Ionosphere data set. This data set is available from the UCI machine learning repository. It is also available directly in R via the mlbench package.

Model training

We will try out a range of models, from simple to complex, in order to try and predict the Class binary outcome. We must specify the resampling scheme and metric to use with caret. In order to assess the models based on the Area Under the Curve (AUC), we must tell caret that the primary performance metric is ROC. caret refers to AUC as ROC. We must specify the summaryFunction argument to be twoClassSummary within the trainControl() function in order to maximize the area under the ROC curve.

Set the resampling control scheme to be 5-fold cross-validation with 3 repeats. We will save the predictions from the cross-validation hold-out sets in order to create ROC curves per fold. We will also instruct caret to return the class predicted probabilities. Specify the resampling controls in the code chunk below.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 3,
                     summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
                     classProbs = TRUE,
                     savePredictions = TRUE)

Generalized linear methods

Start with a simple logistic regression model. We will use all inputs/features within the my_ion data set. The inputs themselves already appear to be normalized between -1 and +1. However, we will preprocess the inputs to study the influence of the relative change on each input compared to the others via standardization. When we wish to include all inputs, we will use the shortcut Class ~ . operator.

Logistic regression

set.seed(4321)
fit_glm <- train(Class ~ ., data = my_ion,
                 method = "glm",
                 metric = "ROC",
                 preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                 trControl = ctrl)

Non-linear methods

We will now try out several complex methods which can capture highly non-linear relationships.

Support vector machines

We will specifically use a Support Vector Machine (SVM) with a radial basis function (RBF) kernel. SVMs are based on the idea of dividing classes through hyperplanes. When a linear separating hyperplane does not exist, SVMs use the âkernel trickâ to transform from the original space to a new feature space. Within this new transformed space, the SVM tries to create linear separating boundaris between the classes. The RBF is particularly well suited for smooth behavior. We will consider the default grid search from caret.

set.seed(4321)
fit_svm <- train(Class ~ ., data = my_ion,
                 method = "svmRadial",
                 metric = "ROC",
                 preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                 trControl = ctrl)

Random forest

The random forest model creates 500 bagged tree models. Compared to a standard bagged tree model, the random forest randomly selects the number of features to consider during the splitting process.

rf_grid <- expand.grid(mtry = c(2, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15))

set.seed(4321)
fit_rf <- train(Class ~ ., data = my_ion,
                method = "rf",
                metric = "ROC",
                trControl = ctrl,
                tuneGrid = rf_grid,
                importance = TRUE)

fit_rf

Model Comparison

Assemble the resampled results together.

model_cv_res <- resamples(list(GLM = fit_glm,
                               GLMNET = fit_glmnet_b,
                               PLS = fit_pls,
                               SVM = fit_svm_b,
                               NNET = fit_nnet_b,
                               RF = fit_rf))

dotplot(model_cv_res)

Based on the Area under the ROC curve (AUC), as ROC as stated by caret, the SVM and random forest are rather similar to each other. The model with the highest Sensitivity is a little surpising they all perform on the same magnitude. Specificity has a clear difference between models.

Now, letâs assumble the ROC curves for comparison. First, we need to identify the best tuned model and combine the cross-validation hold-out set predictions together.

cv_pred_results <- fit_glm$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
  filter(parameter == fit_glm$bestTune$parameter) %>% 
  select(pred, obs, good, bad, rowIndex, Resample) %>% 
  mutate(model_name = "GLM") %>% 
  bind_rows(fit_glmnet_b$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(alpha %in% fit_glmnet_b$bestTune$alpha,
                     lambda %in% fit_glmnet_b$bestTune$lambda) %>% 
              select(pred, obs, good, bad, rowIndex, Resample) %>% 
              mutate(model_name = "GLMNET")) %>% 
  bind_rows(fit_pls$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(ncomp %in% fit_pls$bestTune$ncomp) %>% 
              select(pred, obs, good, bad, rowIndex, Resample) %>% 
              mutate(model_name = "PLS")) %>% 
  bind_rows(fit_svm_b$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(sigma %in% fit_svm_b$bestTune$sigma,
                     C %in% fit_svm_b$bestTune$C) %>% 
              select(pred, obs, good, bad, rowIndex, Resample) %>% 
              mutate(model_name = "SVM")) %>% 
  bind_rows(fit_nnet_b$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(size == fit_nnet_b$bestTune$size,
                     decay == fit_nnet_b$bestTune$decay) %>% 
              select(pred, obs, good, bad, rowIndex, Resample) %>% 
              mutate(model_name = "NNET")) %>% 
  bind_rows(fit_rf$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(mtry == fit_rf$bestTune$mtry) %>% 
              select(pred, obs, good, bad, rowIndex, Resample) %>% 
              mutate(model_name = "RF"))

Letâs also consider the calibration curves associated with the cross-validation hold-out sets for a few of the models. We need to reorganize the fold hold-out results before we can use the build in functions which generate the calibration curves. We will consider the elastic net, the SVM, and the neural network models.

glmnet_test_pred_good <- fit_glmnet_b$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(alpha %in% fit_glmnet_b$bestTune$alpha,
                     lambda %in% fit_glmnet_b$bestTune$lambda) %>% 
              select(obs, good, rowIndex, Resample)

svm_test_pred_good <- fit_svm_b$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(sigma %in% fit_svm_b$bestTune$sigma,
                     C %in% fit_svm_b$bestTune$C) %>% 
              select(obs, good, rowIndex, Resample)

nnet_test_pred_good <- fit_nnet_b$pred %>% tbl_df() %>% 
              filter(size == fit_nnet_b$bestTune$size,
                     decay == fit_nnet_b$bestTune$decay) %>% 
              select(obs, good, rowIndex, Resample)
cal_holdout_preds <- glmnet_test_pred_good %>% rename(GLMNET = good) %>% 
  left_join(svm_test_pred_good %>% rename(SVM = good),
            by = c("obs", "rowIndex", "Resample")) %>% 
  left_join(nnet_test_pred_good %>% rename(NNET = good),
            by = c("obs", "rowIndex", "Resample")) %>% 
  select(Class = obs, GLMNET, NNET, SVM)

And now we can generate the calibration curves for the three models we wish to compare. As shown below, the neural network model over predicts the emprical frequency within each bin, while the SVM under predicts the frequency.

cal_object <- calibration(Class ~ GLMNET + NNET + SVM, 
                          data = cal_holdout_preds,
                          cuts = 10)

ggplot(cal_object) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "top")

Letâs retry with fewer bins. The results appear consistent with calibration curve based on 10 bins, instead of 5. The simpler linear elastic net model appears to be well calibrated, except for he lowest prediceted probability values. However, we already saw that point-wise predictive accuracy metrics were lower for the elastic net model. Itâs important to consider multiple performance metrics in order to get a sense how the model will perform on a point-by-point basis, as well as in the long run.

cal_object <- calibration(Class ~ GLMNET + NNET + SVM, 
                          data = cal_holdout_preds,
                          cuts = 5)

ggplot(cal_object) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "top")
